column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

Numbers remained steady and the quality was a little plainer. There were good numbers of yearlings and there were more lighter weights. Feeders were strong on most weights and grades but were noticeable stronger on the lighter weights either to be feed or background. There were good numbers of trade cattle. The grown steers and heifer were well supplied and most had plenty of cover and weight. The cow run had a few more medium weight 2 and 3 scores but still were well supplied by heavy weights. The market sold to firm to dearer trends.
 
The light feeders or backgrounder were 25c to 30c stronger with the light steers selling from 320c to 399c/kg and the heifers 290c to 326c/kg. Medium weight feeder steers were firm to 3c stronger with crossbreds selling to stronger trends, prices ranged between 338c and 380c/kg and heavy weights reached 377c/kg. Heifers to feed lifted 4c to 6c with medium and heavy weights ranging from 266c to 325c/kg. Heavy trade heifers were stronger while trade steers were firm to slightly cheaper with breed a factor. Trade steers and heifers sold from 290c to 330c/kg.
 
Grown steers and bullocks were firm selling from 280c to 342c/kg. Leaner feeder steers were 6c stronger reaching 364c/kg. Prime heavy grown heifers also similar 270c to 330c/kg. Heavy cows were back slightly with the heavy weights ranging from 250c to 285c, a lot of the heavy cows sold from 275c to 280c/kg. Medium weight 2 score were 4c dearer on average ranging from 230c to 252c/kg
